The new ČSSD councillors in the capital will seem to have to overcome the obvious language barriers for the components of the Prague Board and the City Council to understand their renewed ODS colleagues.
The period Aktuálně.cz "examined" the members of the new ČSSD Council to verify their knowledge of the slang marked language that has emerged in recent years in the Council, when the current members of the coalition ruled Prague.
The encoded dictionary that used Prague's political flower and nata during the previous period, by mayor Pavel Bém, includes some of the most well-known characters, situations and causes of the metropolis.
Surprisingly, it has been proven that the new councillors hardly understand those well-known concepts.
At least so they say.
“Who is Voldemort?”
“The truth is I don’t know.”
“I’m rather a novice in Prague politics,” said Lukáš Kaucký, the councillor for culture, during the terminology examination of “college”.
And as for the veteran politician, Karel Březina reacted equally.
Per you know the concept of “golf hole.”
“Possibly it’s the only expression of all you’ve asked me what I use from time to time.”
“If not, I usually don’t use slang.”
From the glossary, whose definitions the newspaper Aktuálně.cz published last June before the ODS voting congress, the editorial board chose six examples, in particular those that are especially related to the municipal authorities of Prague.
Socialists had to explain the concepts of "Voldemort", "Prague's biggest golf hole", "go to the bakery", "tour neck", "tradition of the capital" and "blinding".
