The nicknames are also the only expressions that the social-democrats tolerate in speech within the party.
Hulínský does not like to be called Hulda, but the newspaper Aktuálně.cz even discovered other nicknames for this Prague president.
"The Doctor of the Rights of the Porras" seems to recall that Petr Hulínský obtained his doctorate in law from the Bratislava police academy.
The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", according to a brochure
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually of old age, cannot work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "return" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
“Men rarely suffer like that.”
"It does not isolate healthy young women, because they help in work and have children," explains a nun who, in the capital of the state of West Africa, Burkina Faso, is occupied in a special residence of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual “social measure”.
He issued an informative pamphlet that should help prevent the witch hunt.
However, this has a trap.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso do not know how to read,” the newspaper Die Standard warns of the disadvantages of writing awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighbouring Burkina Faso, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate cluster of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman was stuck in the oil used for ritual anointings.
He set himself on fire when the group wanted to “expel the evil spirits” from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The Der Standard newspaper quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: “Human soul-eaters have always been a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to calm the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
"Gambian President Jammeh, after his aunt's death, launched a widespread witch hunt that allegedly had been related to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself using black magic."
“To help him he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president’s personal escort, forcibly took randomly chosen men and women from the Gambian peoples to the president’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
In the estate, the arrested people had to drink a pot of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused them intestinal and renal problems.
Two of the arrested did not survive the stay in the estate.
Following international pressure, some 1,000 detainees were finally released.
Bakala tenant: Heats up with coal-fired greenhouses and signs higher rental
The man, aged and smart, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the RPG company Byty of the "coal magnate" Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of rented apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he was carrying documents with the new three-storey rental contracts: his own, his daughter’s and his son’s, who is fulfilling his sentence.
Three of them are now in the process of lease liberalization.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns a month, the son will pay from next year 4,100 crowns for a two-bedroom apartment with separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, he does not have hot water and heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows his finger in his son's new contract, over whose signature he has full powers.
“But I signed it,” he explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new rental conditions "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants do not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing how to proceed in these cases.
But before that, man only makes an ademany.
“Everyone says something,” he said with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a major laboratory for testing liberalization.
After New Year will happen with the vast majority of the apartments that, in the Czech Republic, were until now under a regulated rental.
Therefore, Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of the four in Ostrava and, on Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Just next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a numbering machine.
"Rental 2011" can be read on a bright button on your touch screen.
By pressing it, a paper with a number comes out of the machine.
Almost no time to read "157" and already the number appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you’re in the queue.
Soon after, an elderly marriage arrives to ask, but the crowd of the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, such as previously: arrangement requests, insurance issues and similar matters.
The letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of tenants of most of the 44,000 apartments belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes a rental increase of between 15 and 38 percent.
On November 18, a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
"It's running for a week, so it's beginning," replied, after doubting briefly, the workers who are in it when the client presents himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and Bakala's old miners' floors are the most delicate issues in the area.
Prior to the elections, they were already treated loudly by the vice-president of the Parliament, Ostrava-born Lubomír Zaorálek, of the ČSSD, and now appear continuously in the local newspapers.
“20 years later, I want a new ground.”
“I didn’t even change the damned dish of the bathroom,” the man mentioned in the introduction says.
According to the workers, at the moment more than nothing retired come to check if they get a discount on the rental if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
They will also receive half of the discount on the February rental for the remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15.
However, the window of mining “liberalization” does not manage to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only about forty or fifty people asked for the rental in 2011," the window store employee estimates.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rental, an independent judge must resolve the matter.
"It's not a threat, but information about the only way to proceed possible and completely in accordance with the law," RPG warns on its pages.
"Here no one is going to be judged," says one of the RPG employees Byty and a man who is on the street in front of the customer service center gives her, at least in part, the reason.
"I receive a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 for food; I have no means to go to the courts," he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows the doubt.
“We will see.”
"Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people wait," he said.
The rental regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
"The current rents still do not even cover the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund," recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, who adds that the careless state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for the owners, the main reason to increase the rental.
While during the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG could with rentals invest in apartments four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.200 million.
The large screen that hangs from the ceiling, in front of the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data that highlights in red.
"The rental increase in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, that is, more than 90% of RPG properties."
"In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech crowns per month per square meter," it is indicated on the screen.
Only the rental of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio increased by 38%.
“In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts of 19.66 crowns per square meter,” RPG said.
At 2,600 floors, the rental will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalization will not hit rent, but will escalate between four and eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rental rise (see chart) again in the floors, mainly in saving on heating: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the rental agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need nursery
The administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with everything owned by such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can attend it.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio numerous well-known buildings of Brno came out, thought from the early sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its minigarden.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly in the baby boom age and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying reduced hours, kindergarten is one of the benefits Arch.Design offers its employees as part of its social program.
Builders and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-guard was an idea of Arch.Designu employees themselves and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-guard is financed through the European Social Fund under the Human Resources and Employment Operational Program, as well as from the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the granted funding (a dotation of more than 2.8 million Czech crowns) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When the funding is exhausted (two years), the company Arch.Design has the obligation to keep the minigarden in operation with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted a year and the company Economy Rating contributed to the submission of the funding application.
The care of the children is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day long for their care.
Since it is a "minigarten", it can only simultaneously accommodate a maximum of five children, although with turns they go more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of the parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-care program are comparable to the program of the usual preschool teaching.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach to English.
The class not only has toys and table games, but also a computer for the children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up children late from school when they are away from their workplace.
Parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
Thus, Arch.Design ranks among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened personnel marketing.
The House of Bones still fascinates after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lagoon, the stairs resemble the dinosaur’s column, and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals dubbed it "the house of bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the novel use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade that reminds of the scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all of this is typical of Antoni Gaudí’s secession.
The cover of the house plays with onyrian lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought-out order is observed.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, as it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentea and the twist of the forms continue to surprise us also in its interior.
The wave wood copies the frames of the windows, the bars, the adornments of the doors, the mirrors and the signposts.
The Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample neighborhood in number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, arose from the renovation of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of various apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
It was designed by the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
In fact, in his plans of the project appeared ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the façade.
In the facade also worked other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Casa Batlló was the beginning of the successful collaboration of Jujol with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and the Park Güell de Gaudí, in which other pieces of it are found.
Due to its organic shape, the locals shortly after its completion dubbed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of the bushes".
It is also said that, at the top of the building, the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia appears.
Other sculptural elements of the building hide religious motifs.
Gaudí projected in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation respirators and the typical fireplaces.
It may seem strange its inclination of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect the construction norms of the time at all and did not be influenced by them.
Still, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the municipality was so impacted with the result that it asked to be corrected.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather the opposite: only fifteen days after the request of the municipality, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
On the lower floor was the owner.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewellery.
The six-storey house is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of the connection of space.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the lounges and a larger group can communicate in this way smoothly, without giving up the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with the light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and rainbows.
The game with the two colors brings the maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit the Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and rechargeable apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the famous creator’s birth.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very profitable business and expanded the visits to the common area and the stove, including the roof terrace.
The price of the entrance to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entrance of other Gaudí buildings in the city.
