How to choose the mattress and somer: women and men look for different things
Nothing of a pompous frame for the bed; what really confers its quality to a good bed is the surface to tumble, that is, the mattress and the somer.
First of all, they must be perfectly complemented so that they can be adapted to specific users.
During the choice, numerous elements come into play, including the owner’s weight, height, health status and gender.
Also important is the type of interior in which the mattress and the somer are located.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cottage that doesn’t usually have heating, latex mattresses should not be used because they “heat” more slowly.
In addition, they usually weigh considerably more than the usual polyurethane mattresses.
Therefore, it is necessary to turn them around more often.
If the channels in the center are not properly aired and, above, are on a firm base, they keep the moisture inside.
When choosing a bed, habits also influence.
Those who have spent a lot of time abroad often use a very high mattress with a soft layer and will have trouble feeling good on a lower, tougher surface.
“Nearly all of the hockey players who came back from the NHL complained that they didn’t sleep as well here.”
"For their scratched shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a soft layer of viscoelastic."
"This type of mattress is also recommended for people with diabetes who have nervous system problems, so they get poor information from the joints and skin," says Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, have long preferred viscoelastic mattresses.
"Today there is no problem, because they have these suitable Tempur and the Italian Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico."
You don’t have to be an NHL player anymore to be able to appreciate viscoelastics.
This “miracle” works in a very simple way.
It optimizes its stiffness and shape depending on the heat absorbed or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing exercises pressure; during the night, it won’t turn like after a tough game.
It just sleeps better.
The viscoelastic also acts as protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to its height the length of your feet, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of around 180 cm will need a bed between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for one person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
In the case of single rooms, for example, it is recommended at least between 120 and 140 cm.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
"If not, a simple rule can be applied to calculate the width: by tumbling up, you should have your hands comfortably shrunk to the elbows," advises engineer Helena Prokopová, an expert of Cechu čalouníků a dekoratérů, who has been dealing with the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture for many years, a topic she teaches in specialized schools.
In double rooms, each needs its own mattress and mattress, so during the purchase you should pay attention to combining the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the somers at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, models with interior fence a minimum of 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters are for the layer that suits the shapes and smooth.
"When touching it with your hand or settling on the mattress, you should not notice the folds," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of somer.
Completely coated bedrooms, in which the mattress and base are like Siamese, don’t make sense in the bedroom.
The mattresses breathe badly and you can’t wash their foam, which is often done today.
And, given that every night we sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 liters of sweat, it is clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congestioned) tamis.
For this reason, specialists reject slogans that talk about a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime guarantee.
Everything has a pero.
Therefore, sellers give a tip: in mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, carefully handle the cleaning and washing of the foam, but better add a mattress protector that can be removed and washed easily.
Although mattresses with cremallera closure are currently manufactured throughout their perimeter, so when they are opened they are left in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), their manipulation in larger models (and by a single person) when lifting the mattress can seem like a fight between a fly weight and a heavy weight.
In the bed, instead of a somer, do you have a firm table?
and never !
As much for the beds designed to spend a night visitors.
However, you should make (if you don’t already have them) ventilation holes in the table and it should be used with a mattress with sockets inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with sockets in bags (such as the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft layer.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-articulable blades that contain between 14 and 18 blades, you can use latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (for example, a combination of latex and coconut fiber), although it is always better to use a blade with a greater number of blades, 28 or more, in which the lumbar zone blades are reinforced and their rigidity can be regulated.
Articulable sheet mattresses should not be used with a mattress, as it does not react to reclining.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the blades, shoulder protection can also be used.
It is a special fixation of the blades that allows you to press or even tilt the blades in such a way that they perfectly "round" the shoulders during sleep.
For men who have very wide shoulders, this is something very important.
They are even remembered by mattress manufacturers who, in the "masculines", began to use a softer area precisely around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are cross-structured or tablets with the so-called multitorsion amortization.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the tension is lowered.
You should also keep in mind that, even if you use the right mattress and cushion, if you use a bad pillow (large and "mulled"), most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should hold the head and the corners can only reach the shoulders, so that the muscles of the shoulders can be relaxed.
The appropriate size recommended is 50 x 60 cm, something normal for example in Scandinavia.
When tapping on the side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the shoulder reinforcer or the softest area of the mattress) as the height of the shoulders.
Modern mattresses have something to do, it seems, with the original palm-filled mattresses.
Manufacturers continue to use, more and more often, natural materials or at least mixtures.
In fact, organic mattresses are in fashion.
Oil-based raw materials, from which polyurethane foam is manufactured, are filled with natural oils, such as ricinus or soybeans.
In fact, almost all known manufacturers use soybeans.
“Biological, in the case of mattresses, means that the center is made only of materials of natural origin,” explains Petr Vašíček of the company Tropico Plus.
Also, natural substances are used during the manufacture of the mattress foam, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh aroma to forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men “refresh” themselves with breeze vegetable extracts, so that the mattress foam absorbs heat and refreshes the body, women prefer to “heat” the foam.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so women feel more warm.
Favorites at the moment?
The colours are made of cold foam, which are more porous, with an adapted cell structure, which makes them more permeable than normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of various rigidities of cold foam and visco-elastic allow to manufacture mattresses of various zones that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you seven thousand crowns upwards.
Those who perform a therapeutic function usually have a lower VAT, since they are considered as sanitary means.
The first to get this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It is difficult to save on mattresses and somers.
Sometimes you can approve the offers of manufacturers or sellers, who sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a memory foam attached to the foam for 11,990 crowns.
The second one is obtained for free.
The era of viscoelasty with an open cell structure and a great density began with Tempur's "cosmic" material.
It originally appeared as a material for NASA, because during the takeoffs many astronauts were subjected to an enormous overload.
Tempur softens with heat and hardens with cold.
Consequently, the human body, warm, exerts a perfect effect and optimally adapts its pressure.
Therefore, it is ideal to prevent sores from occurring, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
Viscoelastic foam is not only used in mattresses, but also for sanitary products, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
Domestic manufacturers, for example, use the foam Eucatherm C or Twinsaver and similar.
More and more parents use people tracking devices to monitor their children
Fear of children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially intended for the tracking of vehicles, can also track the movement of people and contribute thus, for example, in the case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old girl Anička Janatková.
At the moment, the device is approximately the size of a light bulb box, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a clock.
Many people were frightened by the case of the missing Anička and began to report on the available means to better protect their children.
Even at the expense of invading your privacy.
"We're all trying to tell ourselves that it's not about spying, but another way to reduce the chances of a tragedy," said Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
“I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they get into someone’s pocket without their knowledge, but we haven’t yet stumbled upon such cases.”
“Most customers actually buy it for safety reasons,” Pilin adds.
In their opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns about the fact that if the child does not want to take it, he will simply throw it away.
“Even younger children show great creativity when it comes to intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid being controlled.”
"Before, parents relied enormously on mobile phones, but they could be turned off as easily as the tracking device," Bočková says.
In their opinion, it is questionable whether in the event of an attack such a device is really useful.
“If it’s a prepared kidnapping, the perpetrator will almost always check if the child carries any kind of electronic device that can reveal his or her location.”
“Now is the phone.”
“As the use of tracking devices spreads, they will also look for them, since their sale will be done with a lot of advertising.”
“In such cases, the offenders are always one step ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even in the event that, after an attack, the tracking device is immediately destroyed, its presence can serve as a help.
"You can configure the device to regularly send the position after a certain period of time."
"If he suffers damage, at least it will facilitate the last position of the person in question."
“The more expensive devices have an integrated slope meter, so if the person simply slides and stays immobile, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question,” says Čech.
In their opinion, a service of this type can even be obtained with smart phones with navigation, in which only special software should be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment they are devices with a size similar to a light bulb box or smaller mobile phones.
Therefore, they can be lost.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, that’s why tests are currently being carried out with devices that look like a digital clock.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential aggressor may not identify the device."
"Or that he identifies him after a certain time, which can make the police make time," he adds.
Even if the tracking devices are carried on the wrist or hanging, they will continue to use the same technology that is used for vehicle tracking.
This is the position check with a GPS system (used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough meches to surround all of the Czech Republic, but they only last two years.
The Czech army purchased 445 kilometers of mecha to capture explosives.
Last year, the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of mecha to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the life of the mecha is two years, four at most.
The army bought the explosive mecha from the STV Group, a.s. for forty million crowns.
The General's staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of mecha by saying that the soldiers need for training maneuvers 60 kilometers of mecha a year.
According to the calculations of the army's pyrotechnics, with whom MF DNES was contacted, it is however decided that, in such a case, such manoeuvres should be carried out with frequent use of explosives each year and all generals, high command officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
Neither Defense Minister Alexandr Vondr nor Army Captain Vlastimil Picek wanted exemptions.
Only in this way could it be justified that the army would spend sixty kilometers of mecha.
This is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if that were the case, the army would have sufficient stocks for more than ten years.
If, on the contrary, as experts say, for the initial training of each new professional comes with a maximum of two meters of mecha, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of engineering or special units) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade personally complained recently to Minister Vondra because they say they barely have ammunition for various weapons, so even the practices of shooting for money are limited.
And let’s not talk about the lack of underwear.
“I also don’t get to understand that we are being bought repeatedly such amounts of mecha.”
“But it’s their decision and they’ll undoubtedly know why they act like that.”
“For us, the army is a good customer that, as a company, we try to satisfy,” admits STV Group Commercial Director Jan Děcký.
Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pejšek defends the hundreds of kilometers of mecha and says it will have stocks of this "munition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký, of STV Group, indicates that the mecha only has a service life of four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or the police, of two years.
"If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four," says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its service life, each ammunition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm the soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of mecha, he obtained a discount.
"It cost us 60% less than last year's order of 244 kilometers," said Pejšek, a spokesman for the Defense Ministry's shopping center.
Just for comparison: the annual mecha consumption of the police pyrotechnics, which remove the ammunition of World War II or that left by the Soviet army, does not exceed 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always only ask for the right amount to exhaust the ammunition before its service life ends.
They decided for safety reasons for the pyrotechnics and, in addition, in the meantime, more modern and reliable types of mecha can be obtained.
The Ministry already has clear difficulties to finish tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the Warsaw Pact era, when the two hundred thousand-man Czechoslovak army was preparing for a campaign in the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years the following problem with the current one will occur: hundreds of kilometers of old mecha, which is now being bought "cheaply", will have to be removed.
