A survey that uncovered ridiculous rules
The Absurdez survey of the year is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
It has already eliminated some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurd Survey of the Year was the obligation to bring to the administration documents that officials can access online.
The decision was adopted by more than one-third of the almost four thousand voters.
For example, the social security administration asked for a trade register extract, although its officials can get it with two mouse moves.
Thanks to the survey, this has changed.
"The Czech Social Security Administration will no longer ask for a trade register extract when it carries out a check of the insured's charges," Jana Buraňová, a spokeswoman for ČSSZ, said.
The aim of the Absurd Survey of the Year is to consult the rules and regulations that companies and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic must respect and try to eliminate those that are absurd.
This year, for the fourth time, he participates in the business tournament of the Hospodářské noviny publication and also begins to create affection among the general public.
While last year’s edition had the participation of three thousand voters, this year it virtually reached four thousand.
And it’s not surprising, since we still have several overwhelming legal obligations that need to be respected simply to trade.
"Per in the number of papers needed for tax returns we are in the first place in the world," says Karel Havlíček of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
For years, simplifying business rules has been a declared goal of all governments.
However, compared to the rest of the world, the situation is improving especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, from the point of view of the conditions for having a company, the Czech Republic is in the 74th position, that is, eight places worse than last year.
The Absurd of the Year contest was held for the first time in 2006 and is repeated every year in the same way.
Anyone can indicate some administrative or bureaucratic absurdity each year between April and the end of September, when the contest closes.
The proposals can be made on the website www.firmaroku.cz. Then the competition organizer selects seven candidates for the "antipremio" and, during October, allows the public to vote on the Internet through www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
It wins the absurd who gets the most votes.
More than a hundred were submitted for this year’s survey, including 105 rules and regulations that don’t make sense.
The examples sent them both entrepreneurs as well as professional associations and journalists.
Among the “finalists” of the competition was, for example, the requirement that vehicles for the maintenance of roads and highways pay the toll or that entrepreneurs with twenty employees, two offices and two toilets paint the walls every two years.
The list of the 70 proposals this year is published on the competition pages.
The announcement of the contest, which always takes place at the beginning of November in Prague’s Wenceslas Square, is part of an event in which political and social personalities often participate.
This year, for example, Eva Svobodová, Director of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, or Petr Kužel, President of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic, attended this competition.
“Economic prosperity cannot beined if the state continuously blocks entrepreneurs, so my goal is to eliminate every year at least thirty paragraphs that currently unnecessarily complicate trade,” said Martin Kocourek, Minister of Industry and Trade.
Efforts to eliminate absurd regulations do not go into drunkenness.
In 2007, what bothered people most was the obligation of the entrepreneur to communicate with a three-day notice to the business office of the permanent operation area, the intention to go with a job to a fair or exhibition.
This obligation was removed in the new industrial law.
The obligation that ended second in number of votes in 2007, that is, the communication to the work office by its foreign workers of work trips of up to 30 days, was removed in the law of the so-called green card.
The third is the winner.
The absurdity of 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have in their consultation a large mirror, a fridge and two floor basics.
