The young Czechs are drunk with Fernet and rum.
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause young drinkers under the age of fifteen to end up in medical care.
Children who end up in the hospital continuously to overcome the resaca are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors who encounter such cases in the hospital's pediatric admissions.
Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because it takes a long time to get drunk.
“Now the fashion is strong alcoholic beverages,” says Luděk Pelikán, head of pediatrics at the Hořovice Hospital in the center of Bohemia.
“When they catch a bottle of whisky to their father, it may be whisky, but it’s usually Fernet and vodka.”
“Wodka has the advantage that it’s ally with juice and that it doesn’t smell so much,” she explains.
This was confirmed by Motol University Hospital spokeswoman Eva Jurinová.
“Normally, it’s usually Fernet or Ron.”
“These are modern alcoholic beverages, among schoolchildren.”
"In some cases, they use watermelon they picked up at home," Jurinová adds.
According to Chief Pelikán, drunkards between the ages of thirteen and fourteen are the ones who usually appear in hospitals.
Prior to Hořovice, where he has been working since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics at Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
“A girl had to enter maybe four times.”
"It started at the age of twelve, when she was brought with 3.5 of alcohol in the blood, in addition to a mixture with ecstasy," the department's doctor said.
"He was at the fair of Holešovice at some dance party."
"The interesting thing is that his mother was not surprised that his daughter disappeared for 48 hours," he said.
It is precisely the lack of interest of parents or even their clear tolerance for drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of increased alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, we cannot speak about dependence.
“Alcoholic is a person who has a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children.”
"In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment," says Pelikán.
According to the spokeswoman Jurinová, this year in the Motol pediatric clinic, forty drunk children were hospitalized until mid-November.
However, the statistics only show those who go with severe intoxication and need to stay in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after ambulant medical recognition, go home with their parents or with the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases in which children simply gather after school and drink water, there are three seasonal highlights to mention for Pelikán: Witch Day, Year's End and the end of school.
"In such circumstances, they drink for bad notes or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
“On Witch’s Day, I’ve seen up to seven drunk children in admissions at a time,” Pelikán adds.
Drinkers who spend the night in detoxification under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible rash at home.
The morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided by the injection of a serum with glucose and the nutrients that are lacking in the body.
"These do it much better, because after the busy night, they get up well and it doesn't hurt them."
“They are only confused about where they are,” Pelikán says, adding that, often, patients lose their mood at least when they see the expenses they have generated.
Transportation by ambulance and hospitalization in a room for serious patients comes to cost a dozen thousand crowns.
"I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when on the visit I tell the children directly how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a youth job so that you earn enough to pay for that night," Pelikán adds.
Medical insurance, in his opinion as a regressive measure, which usually returns people the costs of treatment, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
Two L-159s for the first time in foreign hands in Spain
Two L-159s out of a total of five, by which the Czech Defense Ministry replaced the Casa C-295M, departed on Tuesday for Seville, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa - EADS is located.
This is the first time that such a device is in the hands of someone other than the Czech army.
At the moment, they were only abroad to carry out practice or demonstration flights.
The L-159T1 was used by the Czech Army and was still in flight.
The three remaining planes are the L-159 monoplaces.
These are still preserved at Aer Vodochody and the sales intermediary, the company Omnipol, already took over them last week.
Jan Peješk, from the defense press department, says it is not yet known when the aircraft will be physically withdrawn from Vodochody.
“The L-159 monoplace aircraft, on the other hand, were separated from the aircraft repaired a long time ago, without any additional investments or contributions from the Ministry.”
"The L-159T1 were exchanged in their current state," Pejšek told Právo.
He added that the army did not remain without biplace aircraft, since in May 2009 the army signed with Aer Vodochody a contract for a sum of 200 million crowns for the construction of four unnecessary L-159 aircraft for biplaces.
One of the new aircrafts was already received by the army in July, the other will be delivered by the end of the year.
According to Pejšek, EADS has committed to adding the aircraft to the equipment of some allied countries.
"In the contract it is clearly stated that EADS is the company that will withdraw the L-159 aircraft and that they will serve for the practices of pilots from NATO countries."
"It is therefore up to the buyer to decide how he will use them in this framework," says Pejšek.
The newspaper Hospodářské noviny published earlier that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
