The current defense management says the exchange promotes future exports of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army has acquired 72 aircraft from Aer and only uses 24, so it wants to sell the rest.
The purchase of aircraft may have legal consequences.
The European Commission has already sued the Czech Ministry of Defence before the European Court of Justice because it should choose the aircraft by conducting a European tender and not by contacting a single manufacturer.
The army has already received three Casa aircraft and the latter should arrive at Prague’s Kbely airport in fourteen days.
A longer index finger than the anular finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have the longer index than the anular are subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday in a British journal on cancer.
It could depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
“Our results indicate that the relative length of the finger can constitute a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, for men up to the age of 60,” said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Research on Cancer at the University of Warwick.
Consequently, the finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, in particular whether this feature is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, according to Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed with a British counterpart more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the right-hand index finger shorter than the anular.
They had the same chances of developing prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were of the same length.
In the case of men with a longer index than the ring finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men under 60% the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the matrix.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies have indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knows the study, but that he does not think the relationship between the length of the fingers and cancer can be "completely demonstrated".
