Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as well as support for private companies.
Crime is worse than unemployment.
Moreover, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the findings of the latest Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it allows for a follow-up of attitude changes in the region.
The results of this year’s survey, conducted in September and early October, highlight two related issues.
The first is the relatively animated humor reigning in Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in various South American Pacific coastal countries (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% annually since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a reduced 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after a large drop in production last year.
However, only half of respondents from Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see chart 2).
Around 44% of respondents in the region said they were satisfied with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but considerably higher than 25% recorded in 2001 (Chart 3).
Around 34% said they trusted their country’s Congress and 45% their government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but considerably higher compared to 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turmoil in Latin America severely affected support for democracy.
The fact that it has remained during the global financial crisis is probably due to the fact that numerous Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social security network has helped protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only increased marginally in 2009 and has fallen again this year, to 32%.)
However, mood varies considerably from country to country (see chart 4).
Brazil’s good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general feeling of progress.
This feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the polls began, more respondents in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem their country faces (see chart 5).
Around 31% say they or a close relative have been a victim of crime in the past year, a figure that has decreased from 38% last year and is the lowest percentage since 1995.
More positive economic returns are reflected in greater support for private enterprises and the market economy: around 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprises are indispensable for development, compared to only 56% in 2007 (see chart 6).
Around 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela think the same (and 80% support private companies), although their leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country that has the highest leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of respondents (from 18% last year), followed by the United States (from 9% last year) and Venezuela (from 9% a year ago).
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
