A microbe resistant to arsenic poses the possibility of new forms of life on Earth... or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new forms of life on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although researchers discovered the curious bacterium here on Earth, they say it demonstrates that it is possible that there are life forms without the main elements they considered essential.
It has a double capacity.”
"It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"That makes it something very peculiar, although it lacks little to be a kind of really 'alien' form of life," said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report that appears in the online edition of Thursday's Science publication.
For a long time, it has been considered that there are six major essential elements for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, researchers have discovered that the bacterium, found in Mono Lake, California, may continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“It makes you wonder what else is possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the finding is important for the search for life on planets different from Earth, given that researchers need to be able to recognize life, know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the call for a press conference to discuss it, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, generated a lot of speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report indicated the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He did not.
What the discovery "yes shows is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to drive their biochemistry and that the set of "standard" elements that we consider indispensable for life may not be so fixed," said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is new because it demonstrates the substitution of one element by another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure," Cockell added.
The discovery was not by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s astrobiology institute, who led the study, focused on the Mono Lake because it has elevated levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar chemically, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace one by another.
“Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus.”
"As a result, it can be difficult for organizations to differentiate them."
"H, arsenic is different enough that it doesn't work as well as phosphorus, so it enters and, in some way, appeals to the biochemical machinery," Anbar explains.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they managed to adapt and use to grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus, but the fact of demonstrating that it can live with arsenic instead poses the possibility that a form of life that uses arsenic can exist naturally, either in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an auxiliary professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic can be replaced with phosphorus is not new, but there was never an example to prove it works.
Arsenic was most common in the early epochs of Earth, he noted, so researchers speculated that early life forms may have used it.
“It suggests that there could be other means of generating life, not just the way life was formed on Earth in ancient times,” said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
