Can civism build a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invectivity and negativity, a little civism has unleashed in Washington this week.
Is it a pronouncement of a genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick turn to party combat in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and Congress leaders produced no progress on the major issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But by what everyone says, it was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to earn party points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit committee was equally civilized, despite the political differences that persist among the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates the members.
That is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a test period, polling each other to identify signs of cooperativism and commitment, while trying to evaluate the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed party war.
The reason why the Tuesday meeting and subsequent evaluations of the same by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and are too deeply rooted as to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
“There’s no doubt that things have changed in terms of how things are said,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
They are inevitable after the elections.
Elections awaken party passions, which then disappear.
That is good.”
On some issues, those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and nobody is in favor of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to extending unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans can’t make them believe they’re in favor of tax cuts for the wealthy, denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s White House meeting, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new nuclear disarmament treaty START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanism when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He argued, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
“After the things that need to be done are done, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to a confrontational one,” he said.
Also Wehner expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civism could lead to true cooperation.
“I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as an essay for the major event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
No matter how conscious Republican leaders are of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they should try to fulfill their promises of cutting state spending and repealing the new health law.
These party lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the deficit commission’s recommendations, which include the tax code reform and the increase of some taxes and retirement age, and spending cuts.
Co-Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the toughest tasks in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forcibly put the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18 member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The biggest resistance is among the elected officials in the panel, suggesting that in tax matters there is, at least currently, little basis or desire for commitment.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between Republicans in the White House and those in Congress.
The first will take place next year in the form of party shocks, when Republicans challenge Obama over budget, taxes and medical care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the recent election partyism, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead spot, as it happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the people.
Anyone who considers that they are losing will likely change course and seek compromise.
However, this can be an optimistic view.
Partisanism and polarization are currently greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans in Congress than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find points in common on the issues that still divide them.
