On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has advanced new adjustment measures, from tax reductions to SMEs, regulation of private agencies of placement or suppression of the 426 euros of aid to unemployed, to the privatization of 49% of AENA, the management of the airports of Barajas and El Prat and the 30% of State Lotteries.
Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, has joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility to unleash the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
Keep in mind that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another turning point in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which collides with the preservation of the old traditions of much of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany begins to speculate on the three possible outputs to the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would abandon the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the framework, although it now looks like science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigour, fines to the transgressors, possible suspension of payments from some of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government took out a constitutional reform to prevent them from starting in 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be done (planes for fiscal rigour and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second in the front was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully extended the decision to rescue Greece.
Already then it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public and public opinion were very opposed to the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again emerges with a clear position, demanding the reform of the EU treaties, to make it possible to save a country and, at the same time, to force private lenders to run with part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But its proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should attend the process of reform of the Union that enables those measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And it is telling us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we may not agree very much, from that date the old functioning of the euro will have ended.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary area, in which countries who violate will be severely sanctioned, may be forced to declare in suspension of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also bear part of the cost.
Germany is pointing out that we must follow a severe path of growth with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive foreign balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, like the one that has dominated Spanish growth in the years of the boom, will simply not tolerate it.
The sending is clear.
And we would hurt not to understand it.
It is not just about bringing the government deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What they demand is much harder.
And the worst we could do in these circumstances is fool ourselves.
I hope the current turbulence leaves way for more tranquility.
And let us take advantage of the window of opportunity that we have been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood this and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after the meeting last Saturday with large companies and the announcement yesterday of new measures) suggests that, despite the criticisms of Merkel, the thesis that order must be put at home has been opened.
But the red line that Germany has drawn there is, and it doesn’t seem to move it.
And, among the possibilities that are contemplated, the possibility of leaving a monetary zone too full of unserious countries cannot be ruled out.
Then Germany will always be able to tell us that it had already warned us.
Sport and law fraud
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the will to escape a sanction.
The alleged expulsion by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether such behavior is anti-sports and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by the UEFA.
As is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the match (which his team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time when drawing out all sorts of shortcomings to provoke the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In that way, and since Real Madrid will end up as the leader of their group, both players will meet the regulatory sanction the next match of the league, against the Auxerre, and can go clean of cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned the team’s coach, José Mourinho, with two matches, and the players involved with different financial amounts.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the rules not written, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate arising in the case is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem presumes of nobility and honor, and which in past occasions has fined its players for analogous acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds an episode more to his dilated history of technician histrionic and provocative.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, if these actions are committed law fraud; since, in fact, they are actions respectful of the sports regulation, but they seem to circumvent its meaning.
The question goes to examine the type of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that the sporting spirit comprises is the physical integrity of the opposing players, aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these goods that is referred to by the clean game is to prevent the team of the offender players from taking advantage of the opposing team unfairly, which also did not happen.
Now, the paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it did not accommodate what we normally characterize as a trap or law fraud, because their violation of the rules was not done in hiding to try to avoid the sanction, but that precisely their action tried to be the most obvious to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and accepted the punishment.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders get in the deliberate misconduct examined.
Here it seems necessary to see that the rival is not placed in a disadvantageous situation or gained in the same game, because obviously the result of the action means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it’s not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club won’t be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indetermination, because the team can be eliminated at the first changes, and in addition with this performance the players meet a penalty game and pass to the second card cycle, in which the suspension for accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, from going through rounds, it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the spirit of sport, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favor taking the most out of what the rules allow.
In the case that occupies us, the players did not act to evade the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without drawing out the punishment or escaping it.
Although the boundary between ingenuity and law fraud is diffuse, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I think, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and the way in which the transmission of the directive of provoking them was carried out.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
