The peculiarity of Pakistan’s nuclear program – that weapons are not assembled but are stored in components to make it difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack – is one of the main reasons for disregard in Washington.
Ambassador to Pakistan Anne W. Patterson said in a report before the visit of then-National Security Adviser James Jones: “The proximity of some nuclear facilities to territory under Taliban attack, the rumored dispersal of nuclear materials and the vulnerability of the transport of nuclear materials.”
