China holds targets to reduce greenhouse gas emissions
The country’s representative at COP16 assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and detailed that it supports its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020.
China remains committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and to reconvert its industry.
In fact, he said, in the last four years his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made it clear that China will not change its goals, but will continue to work jointly with the international community on that matter.
China’s climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity building; institutional building; and support for pilot programs.
In all these areas progress has been made, including the approval, last year, of a new Energy Law, which includes the objectives set in terms of reduction of gas emissions, he explained.
On the other hand, he noted that in China, federal authorities have been working in coordination with state and local authorities to energy savings, energy efficiency and emissions reduction targets.
In addition, various multiannual plans, both funded by the Chinese government and by governments of other countries, are in progress or have already been concluded.
For example, he referred to the Energy Efficiency Programme, which was implemented over the past five years and received investments from the United Nations (UN), government and private initiative.
There is also a provincial climate change project, another for the change of incandescent focuses by savers and one more for mitigation and adaptation, he detailed.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the government’s scientific adviser on climate change, assured that China’s efforts have been greater than generally thought.
For example, he explained, per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China are six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9 percent of the historic contribution to pollution.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in the use of energy, such as increasing energy efficiency by 20 percent in the past five years and plans to do another so much towards 2020, he said.
