Changing the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals will have to go to the Visa Applicants Service Center before their interview at the Consular Section; the cost will be lower as well as the waiting time.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedure for obtaining a visa at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the Visa Applicants Service Centers (ASC) before their interview at the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will take the applicant’s biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for aspirants, among which are:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment for the appointment, another payment for processing the visa application and another more for the messaging service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current fee will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for merchant and investor visas.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their footprints.
Because biometric information will be taken at the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed at the Consular Section will stay at the ASC for less time than in the past.
Likewise, those applying for a visa at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For additional information about the new procedure for applying for a visa, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
