A global plan to renew lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancun a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to reduce greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions in a amount that corresponds to virtually one-third of the additional decrease that must be carried out to stabilize the planet’s climate before 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of large concrete projects that the UN expects to adopt in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluorocompact bulbs or, even better, by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), much of the 1.800 million tons (Gt) of GEI emitted on the planet would be avoided to illuminate humans.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the global car park.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitter countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce global GEE emissions from 53 to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of this quantity should still be reduced to stabilize, before 2020, the increase in temperatures by two degrees Celsius to prevent it from uncontrolled.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluorescent compact bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced even more than twice.
Compact fluorescent bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, allowing us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would apply in a hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also work with reostates and emit very little heat.
They do not contain mercury.
Several experts have expressed concerns about compact fluorescent bulbs, as they contain mercury and should be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers place instructions.
However, the report indicates, the main source of mercury emission on the planet are not fluorocompact bulbs, but coal-fired thermal plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity that is wasted with incandescent bulbs.
Only in the United States, these power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury a year.
The report details the advantages this international program would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, that is, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it $2.5 billion.
