Avengers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it uncovers an apparent scandal, a scandal that only appears to be a scandal in the face of the hypocrisy that governs the relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and predicts a future dominated by regression.
But let’s go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is composed exclusively of press cuts.
The “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Gaddafi’s sinisterly ridiculous profile has long been giving ideas to cabaret artists to create their sketches.
The rule that secret records should only be made up of news of public knowledge is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars, or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unprecedented research (or do not know where to look for news on the non-existent), but because those who are dedicated to occultism do not just trust what they already know, which confirms what they had already learned.
This is the success mechanism of Dan Brown.
The same applies to secret records.
The informant is lazy, just as the head of the secret services (if he could not be, I know, the editor of the Libération) is lazy (or has little anxiety), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the previous week.
So why have the revelations of these records caused such turmoil?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, namely, that embassies, at least since World War II and since the Heads of States can call by phone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have become centers of espionage.
Anyone who sees research films knows this perfectly, but we only appear that we do not know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact of repeating it publicly breaches the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secret secrets of the world’s most powerful country significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the “verdugos”.
But let’s get into the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, at Orwell’s time, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, hotel visited, motorway taken, the citizen was thus a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as is now the case, that even the crypts of power secrets cannot escape a hacker’s control, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and turns circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, elected as the avenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can one withstand a power that can no longer even keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to take away all power from him.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is evident that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the network, since it would be like publishing it on a poster in the middle of the street.
But it’s also obvious that, with current technologies, you can’t expect to keep confidential phone conversations.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a Head of State has travelled by plane and contacted one of his counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relations in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for now, my forecast is science fiction and, therefore, novel, but I imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, as much as possible, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked cages: after all, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a cable telegraph (telephonic).
The video (analogous) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, advancing and falling back, discovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now the CDs (digital) only allow to advance or fall back from chapter to chapter, that is, to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travel it takes, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the normal that politics and communication techniques take us back to the horse cars.
One last comment.
In ancient times, the press was trying to understand what was secretly handled in the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: France’s hats on its financing promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the promises of rapidly unlocked funding (so-called early starts) made by developed countries have been met.
And the French chopsticks were uncovered.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.260 million (i.e. €420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast-start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation resulted appreciable and was appreciated for what really is worth: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same thing and with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on track to meet its €7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But, if we look at the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be “new and additional” to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what “new and additional” means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
At present, everyone chooses the reference that most suits them.
For example, the European Commission has taken as a reference the year 2009: international funding isined and 150 million in three years is added in the concept of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development aid.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, it does not refer to the expenditure of previous years or the total level of official development aid.
In particular, the total amount of France’s aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while it intends to respect its commitment to “new and additional” funds.
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no standard and everyone chooses the method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that every euro borrowed equals one euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to emission reduction that are based on more effective technologies), it is false to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a donated euro... As a lot, you should only compute for your commitments the cost of the loan for the country that grants the loan (i.e., the equivalent to an interest rate).
But France does not find such a reasoning useful: it “respects” its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); see the EU document to see it with your own eyes.
It is the only country in the EU that uses this loan so frequently.
Germany uses it at 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with a 100% donation.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to meet its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
This is a good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions in time and, on the other hand, in relation to real financial effort.
Spending only 36.1 million euros, he manages to give the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", as he had promised.
The manipulation by the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has taken care of the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other member states continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in negotiations, since developing countries are not stupid...
The early financing chapter is a detail, relatively short-term, in relation to the whole of climate negotiations.
But it could be a grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope it is not so.
Anyway, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention to respect its commitments and in the same way as the rest of the European Union countries.
But, in particular, France could advance the debates on gambling in relation to long-term financing (another key chapter that is currently being discussed): we will not get rid of the question of the “additional character” or the method for computing loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is on other issues.
Therefore, we have the hope of the new Minister of Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast starts and its vision of the “additional character” and the use of loans would contribute to improving the level of international confidence needed to advance the negotiations.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published on Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the former movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results “do not have a significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated,” acquired in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that a ten-year-old child usually consumes in four meals and one tentempié a day.
These model meals, which comply with official recommendations (five portions of fresh fruits and vegetables, three portions of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day), as well as sweets, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five are classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies from various institutions such as the International Centre for Research on Cancer.
“Al, in virtually all cases, the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that consumers’ exposure to potentially carcinogenic pollutants and/or PE is worrying,” the association said.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about a dozen residues that can damage the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a tentempié for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenya’s green Jews, included in food, in which the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
Furthermore, Russian filet, tunic, and even the bar of bread or cheese were wrapped with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chlorine.
At dinner, the salmon roll was the most “nutritive” with 34 chemical waste detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat the food in the microwave wasn’t completely clean.
The final risk generated by these “pollutant cocktails” for consumers is “probably underestimated,” the study says.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the gravity of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to halt "the increase of diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 were in cereals.
